Location: Delft, Netherlands
About the team
At Thales Research, Technology & Innovation (RTI) in Delft, we are seeking a security researcher engineer to help find and address future challenges in security. Our security team focuses on developing secure and usable solutions, in which the end-user/operator has the focus of attention. The main activities of the team are currently related to secure information exchange, data centric security, and resilient secure systems. We research and develop minimum viable products and prototypes to solve real world problems with a strong focus on developing new and innovative technologies for future products. Our researchers work with both national and international experts within the business to identify and help address, business challenges in the 5-15 year timescale. You, as the engineer, are expected to create the proof-of-concept demonstrators and support the handover of program code to the business lines that productise the new concepts.
You will work in the security team and in close collaboration with multi-disciplinary researchers and engineers inside and outside of Thales Research & Technology. In practice, you will work closely with the Architecture, Human Factors, and AI research teams researching how to design and build secure and usable demonstrators. Within this role, you will help define the security research roadmap and will present your ideas and concepts to the research and innovation community across the Thales Group. Your ideas will be developed within our team towards integration into new and existing products. We develop concepts from low to mid TRL (1-5), as well as helping transfer our developments into the business. As Thales is a large multi-national company, career possibilities are numerous. Security is a hugely important and growing area within Thales and personal development is strongly encouraged.
About your future job
New security concepts are initiated by our researchers and are aimed to support the strategic needs in the Thales product portfolios. Once validated our innovations have to be realized in proof of concepts and demonstrators in the system domain of our internal stakeholders or external customers. Finally, there is a transition from our research department to the business lines that productise the new concepts into their system environment. The Security Research Engineer validates and realises the initial concepts, realises the proof the concept demonstrators, and supports the hand-over to the units that productise the new concepts. You typically work in a team with researchers and engineers from different disciplines.
We are looking for a Security Research Engineer that has a general interest to work on the above and have a specific interest in one or more of the following areas:
Cryptographic primitives
Secure development processes
Failover resilience
Containerisation
Secure Hardware
SOC/SIEM
Continuous Development processes
